'''Kalabera''' is a small village on the northern side of [[Saipan]] in the [[Northern Mariana Islands]].
Kalabera is best known for a large cave<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mp.geoview.info/kalabera_cave_saipan_is,28536511p|title=Picture of Kalabera Cave|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>, that is a common tourist stop. The entry room stands close to 60 feet high, and drops off to a seemingly bottomless series of tributaries.<ref>[http://www.showcaves.com/english/misc/showcaves/Kalabera.html Kalabera Cave] at showcaves.com</ref> Kalabera is associated with many colonial stories, including being used as a [[prison]] for [[Chamorros]] during [[Spain|Spain's]] colonial period<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/the-mysterious-kalabera/|title=The mysterious Kalabera|last=Mergino|first=Alex|date=6 June 2017|website=saipantribune.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=18 April 2018}}</ref> and a reputed [[officers]] "recreation club" during the [[Japanese military]] occupation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guampedia.com/chamorro-cave-art/2/#Liyang_Kalabera_Saipan|title=» Ancient Chamorro Cave Art|website=www.guampedia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref>
